Selecting Variables and Merging Datasets

Load and examine the examination data form the NHANES 2017 to 2018 dataset

BMI_2018 <- read_xpt("BMX_2018.xpt")
head(BMI_2018, 10)

Data Wrangling

Extract variables needed

BMI_DOI_2018 <- BMI_2018[, c("SEQN", "BMXBMI")]
BMI_DOI_2018 <- BMI_DOI_2018 %>%
  rename(
    ID = SEQN,
    BMI = BMXBMI
  )
head(BMI_DOI_2018,1)

Load and examine data from the NHANES demographic dataset from the 2017-2018 survey

DEM_2018 <- read_xpt("DEMO_2018.xpt")
head(DEM_2018,1)

Extract needed variables

DEM_DOI_2018 <- DEM_2018 %>%
  select("SEQN", "RIAGENDR", "RIDAGEYR", "RIDRETH1", "DMDEDUC2", "INDHHIN2") %>%
  rename(
    ID = SEQN,              # Respondent sequence number
    Gender = RIAGENDR,      # Gender
    Age_Years = RIDAGEYR,   # Age in years
    Race = RIDRETH1,        # Race/Ethnicity
    Education = DMDEDUC2,   # Education level for 20+ adults
    Household_Income = INDHHIN2  # Annual household income
  )

head(DEM_DOI_2018, 1)

Merge the data from the examination and demographic datasets

# before merging, sort datasets by SEQN (unique respondent ID)
BMI_DOI_2018 <- BMI_DOI_2018 %>% arrange(ID)
DEM_DOI_2018 <- DEM_DOI_2018 %>% arrange(ID)
#check sorted datasets
head(BMI_DOI_2018,5)
head(DEM_DOI_2018,5)
data <- merge(BMI_DOI_2018, DEM_DOI_2018, by = "ID") 
head(data, 10)
#and export/save it as csv
write.csv(data, "BMI And Demographic data for the US 2017 to 2018.csv")

Recoding Variables

# Interested in the presence or absence of obesity
# A BMI >= 30 is classified as obese (1), while <30 is not obese (0):
recoded <- filtered_data %>%
  mutate(obesity = ifelse(BMI >= 30, 1, 0),
         #Education level is a categorical variable whereby:
         #1 = Less than 9th grade
         #2 = 9-11th grade (Includes 12th grade with no diploma)
         #3 = High school graduate/GED or equivalent
         #4 = Some college or AA degree
         #5 = College graduate or above
         #recode according to college graduated or not
        College_graduate = case_when(
           Education == 1 ~ 0,
           Education == 2 ~ 0,
           Education == 3 ~ 0,
           Education == 4 ~ 0,
           Education == 5 ~ 1),
         # Recode gender, by introducing a female variable where 1=female, male = 0
         Female = case_when(
           Gender == 1 ~ 0,
           Gender == 2 ~ 1),
         # group hispanics, whites, black and other races
         Race = case_when(
           Race == 1 ~ 1, #Mexican American
           Race == 2 ~ 1, # Other Hispanic
           Race == 3 ~ 2, # non-hispanic Whites
           Race == 4 ~ 3, #black
           Race == 5 ~ 4),#others
         # Recode income with actual estimates
         Income = case_when(
           Household_Income == 1  ~ 2500,
           Household_Income == 2  ~ 7500,
           Household_Income == 3  ~ 12500,
           Household_Income == 4  ~ 17500,
           Household_Income == 5  ~ 22500,
           Household_Income == 6  ~ 30000,
           Household_Income == 7  ~ 40000,
           Household_Income == 8  ~ 50000,
           Household_Income == 9  ~ 60000,
           Household_Income == 10 ~ 70000,
           Household_Income == 12 ~ 17500,
           Household_Income == 13 ~ 22500,
           Household_Income == 14 ~ 85000,
           Household_Income == 15 ~ 100000)
         ) %>%
  mutate(across(c(obesity, Female, Race, College_graduate), 
                as.factor))%>%
  select(obesity, Female, Age_Years, 
         Income, Race,College_graduate)

Modeling The Relationship Between Obesity and Education

Logistic Regression

Since the dependent variable (obesity) is binary (0 = Not Obese, 1 = Obese), logistic regression is best suited for this statistical modelling.

\[ \log \left(\frac{P(Obesity_i)}{1 - P(Obesity_i)}\right) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 (CollegeGraduate_i) + \varepsilon_i \]

Where:

\(\ P(Obesity_i)\) is the probability of being obese. The left-hand side represents the log-odds of obesity. \(\ (\beta_0)\) is the intercept. \(\ (\beta_1)\) represents the effect of college education on obesity. \(\ (\varepsilon_i)\) is the error term.

Since logistic regression works with log-odds, there is need to convert the coefficient into an odds ratio using:

\[ \text{Odds Ratio} = e^{\beta_1} \]

Moreover, the coefficient intervals also need to be computed for the odds ratio: \[ CI = \left(e^{Lower \ CI}, e^{Upper \ CI}\right) \]

# Logistic regression (base model) for obesity and education
logit_edu_model <- glm(obesity ~ College_graduate, data = recoded, family = binomial())
summary (logit_edu_model)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = obesity ~ College_graduate, family = binomial(), 
##     data = recoded)
## 
## Coefficients:
##                   Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)       -0.20267    0.03381  -5.994 2.05e-09 ***
## College_graduate1 -0.53798    0.07166  -7.508 6.01e-14 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 6364.3  on 4680  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 6306.1  on 4679  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 6310.1
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

College graduates have a log odds -0.538, indicating that college graduates are less likely to be obese than non-graduates.This is statistically significant at p<0.0001. Intercept, -0.20267, represents the baseline log-odds of obesity for non-college graduates.

The change in deviance from 6364 in null deviance to 6306 in residual deviance highlights that college education indeed explains some variability in obesity occurence.

The Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) value is quite high, 6310, which suggests that adding more variables could help explain the variability in obesity presence.

# Compute odds ratio
odds_ratio <- exp(coef(logit_edu_model))
# Compute confidence intervals for odds ratios
CI_ratio <- exp(confint(logit_edu_model))

Following conversion to odds ratio, it is evident that college graduates have approximately 41.6% lower odds of being obese compared to non-graduates.

The confidence interval for odd ratios further show that 95% Confidence Interval for the odds ratio indicates a statistically significant negative relationship.

Omitted Variable Bias

Similar to linear regression, if a key explanatory variable is left out, the estimated coefficients might be biased, leading to incorrect conclusions.

Likelihood Ratio Test

This tests if adding more variables significantly improves model fit. Thus, the upadate model formula is:

\[ \log \left(\frac{P(Obesity_i)}{1 - P(Obesity_i)}\right) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 (CollegeGraduate_i) + \beta_2 (Income_i) + \beta_3 (Race_i) + \beta_4 (Age_i) + \beta_5 (Gender) + \varepsilon_i \]

# Full model (adding more predictors)
logit_full_model <- glm(obesity ~ College_graduate + Income + Race + Age_Years + Female, 
                        data = recoded, family = binomial())
summary(logit_full_model)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = obesity ~ College_graduate + Income + Race + Age_Years + 
##     Female, family = binomial(), data = recoded)
## 
## Coefficients:
##                   Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)       -1.25402    0.40323  -3.110  0.00187 ** 
## College_graduate1 -0.40047    0.07811  -5.127 2.94e-07 ***
## Income             0.07979    0.03769   2.117  0.03424 *  
## Race2             -0.04220    0.08170  -0.516  0.60553    
## Race3              0.18596    0.08901   2.089  0.03668 *  
## Race4             -0.94755    0.10320  -9.182  < 2e-16 ***
## Age_Years          0.04325    0.01633   2.649  0.00806 ** 
## Female1            0.18008    0.06082   2.961  0.00307 ** 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 6364.3  on 4680  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 6143.2  on 4673  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 6159.2
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4
#likelihood ratio test
anova(logit_edu_model, logit_full_model, test = "Chisq")

The likelihood ratio test suggests that Model 2 (which includes additional variables: Income, Race, Age, and Female) significantly improves the fit compared to Model 1 (which only has College Graduate as a predictor). Deviance Drop = 162.89, which is quite substantial. Difference = 6 df (which matches the number of additional predictors added):Income, Race2(White), Race3(Black), Race 4(others), Age, and Female. Most importantly: The significance test (Likelihood Ratio Test): p-value < 2.2e-16 (extremely significant) This means that adding Income, Race, Age, and Female significantly improves model fit.

AIC score improves by around 150 points. Further showing the improved fit of the model. Additionally, the coefficient for college education shows a decrease in effect from -5.38 to -0.4 after controlling for other variables. This suggests that the initial model overestimated the effect of college education, but the relationship remains negative.

It is seen that income, and obesity have a positive relationship, similar to the female gender and an increase in age.

It is also crucial to understand that since Race is a categorical variable containing four races, the regression model takes the first Race variable, Race =1 or Hispanic, as a reference variable and create dummy variables for other 3 categories. Hence, it compares its effect on obesity to the other 3 races. Therefore, being white is more likely to lead to obesity compared to being Hispanic, however, this is not statistically significant. Being black is likely to effect obesity more than being Hispanic. However, other races have a negative effect on being obese. These include Asians and Arabs etc.
